Three dataframe types — keep them straight.

This is the same three-way distinction we drew back in module four — and it comes back here, because it is the axis that everything in this module turns on.

The first is the pandas dataframe. It lives in driver memory only. Use it for final-mile analysis, for plotting, and for small fixtures.

The second is the pandas-on-Spark dataframe. It is distributed across the executors. Use it when you want pandas syntax, but at Spark scale.

And the third is the Spark dataframe. It is also distributed, and it is the native interface — the best performance, and the most features.

Only the first one lives on the driver. The other two are distributed, over the very same engine. And pandas-on-Spark, specifically, is just a Spark dataframe, with a pandas-style index added on top. Hold on to that detail — because that added index is exactly the source of the gotchas, later in this module.
